Advisory is based on visual monitoring for indicators of harmful algal bloom and trigger public health posting of “caution” advisory level.
Advisory applies to the full extent of the lake or reservoir (lake-wide advisory) and is not to limited the location symbolized by this report.

Observations at this site include confirmation of harmful algal bloom that  forms potential toxic algal mats that grow attached to cobble, sand, and plants on the bottom of the waterway. The water can appear clear when algal mats are attached to the bottom. These mats can dislodge and float downstream or strand on the shoreline, children and dogs should avoid touching mat material.

AdvisoryDetail: Alert-high concentration toxins; Bottom/benthic bloom observed
Advisory_Detail_Description: Alert! High concentration of one or more cyanotoxins measured at this site indicating elevated health risk to humans and animals.  Observations at this site include confirmation of harmful algal bloom that  forms potential toxic algal mats that grow attached to cobble, sand, and plants on the bottom of the waterway. The water can appear clear when algal mats are attached to the bottom. These mats can dislodge and float downstream or strand on the shoreline, children and dogs should avoid touching mat material.

AdvisoryDetail: Lake-wide advisory; Marine bloom present (red tide)
Advisory_Detail_Description: Advisory applies to the full extent of the lake or reservoir (lake-wide advisory) and is not to limited the location symbolized by this report.  Marine bloom or “red tide” reported in this area. Red tides appear reddish-brown color and can cause marine animal impacts, particularly for fish. CA Water Boards agency recommends people and pets avoid contact with the water during times of any dense blooms or discoloration in the water. People exposed to marine algae blooms via water contact may experience irritation of the eyes, skin, or respiratory system. Report any illnesses of human or animals (domestic and wild) to https://tinyurl.com/HABReport1. More information about marine harmful algal blooms is available on Dept. of Public Health’s Marine Biotoxin Monitoring Program webpage at: https://tinyurl.com/5e8uc9k4.

Reported_Management_Organizations: R2 was contacted by San Mateo County Parks and Bay Keeper about this bloom because they wanted help testing it. R2 recommended they reach out to Vanessa at CDPH. San Mateo county is posting the caution planktonic HAB sign in response to this observation. Bay Keeper reported ~25 dead striped bass and a white sturgeon in the area that appeared to be within the bloom.
Advisory_Detail_Description: Marine bloom or “red tide” reported in this area. Red tides appear reddish-brown color and can cause marine animal impacts, particularly for fish. CA Water Boards agency recommends people and pets avoid contact with the water during times of any dense blooms or discoloration in the water. People exposed to marine algae blooms via water contact may experience irritation of the eyes, skin, or respiratory system. Report any illnesses of human or animals (domestic and wild) to https://tinyurl.com/HABReport1. More information about marine harmful algal blooms is available on Dept. of Public Health’s Marine Biotoxin Monitoring Program webpage at: https://tinyurl.com/5e8uc9k4.

AdvisoryDetail: Lake-wide advisory; Marine bloom present (red tide); Suspected bloom, investigation ongoing
Advisory_Detail_Description: A suspected harmful algal bloom was reported, an investigation is underway and this report will be updated once info is provided by the responding organizations.  Advisory applies to the full extent of the lake or reservoir (lake-wide advisory) and is not to limited the location symbolized by this report.  Marine bloom or “red tide” reported in this area. Red tides appear reddish-brown color and can cause marine animal impacts, particularly for fish. CA Water Boards agency recommends people and pets avoid contact with the water during times of any dense blooms or discoloration in the water. People exposed to marine algae blooms via water contact may experience irritation of the eyes, skin, or respiratory system. Report any illnesses of human or animals (domestic and wild) to https://tinyurl.com/HABReport1. More information about marine harmful algal blooms is available on Dept. of Public Health’s Marine Biotoxin Monitoring Program webpage at: https://tinyurl.com/5e8uc9k4.

AdvisoryDetail: Marine bloom suspected (red tide); Under investigation
Advisory_Detail_Description: Marine bloom or “red tide” are suspected in this area. Red tides appear reddish-brown color and can cause marine animal impacts, particularly for fish. Until water monitoring results are provided to confirm presence of red tide in this area, we recommend people and pets avoid contact with the water during times of any water discoloration or dense blooms in the water. People exposed to marine algae blooms via water contact may experience irritation of the eyes, skin, or respiratory system.   This report is under investigation.

AdvisoryDetail: Marine bloom present (red tide); Suspected bloom, investigation ongoing
Advisory_Detail_Description: A suspected harmful algal bloom was reported, an investigation is underway and this report will be updated once info is provided by the responding organizations.  Marine bloom or “red tide” reported in this area. Red tides appear reddish-brown color and can cause marine animal impacts, particularly for fish. CA Water Boards agency recommends people and pets avoid contact with the water during times of any dense blooms or discoloration in the water. People exposed to marine algae blooms via water contact may experience irritation of the eyes, skin, or respiratory system. Report any illnesses of human or animals (domestic and wild) to https://tinyurl.com/HABReport1. More information about marine harmful algal blooms is available on Dept. of Public Health’s Marine Biotoxin Monitoring Program webpage at: https://tinyurl.com/5e8uc9k4.

AdvisoryDetail: Marine bloom present (red tide); Under investigation
Advisory_Detail_Description: Marine bloom or “red tide” reported in this area. Red tides appear reddish-brown color and can cause marine animal impacts, particularly for fish. CA Water Boards agency recommends people and pets avoid contact with the water during times of any dense blooms or discoloration in the water. People exposed to marine algae blooms via water contact may experience irritation of the eyes, skin, or respiratory system. Report any illnesses of human or animals (domestic and wild) to https://tinyurl.com/HABReport1. More information about marine harmful algal blooms is available on Dept. of Public Health’s Marine Biotoxin Monitoring Program webpage at: https://tinyurl.com/5e8uc9k4.  This report is under investigation.

Landmark: Midpeninsula Open Space District Skyline Field Office
Bloom_Size: between a tennis court and a sedan
Reported_Management_Organizations: This pond lies within the District's Skyline Ridge Open Space Preserve and is a non-contact recreation waterbody. District staff collected surface water and floating mat grab samples and submitted them to Bend Genetics for toxin analysis. Results of the surface water sample show non-detection. Results of the floating mat show presence of Lyngbya sp. with 0.16 ug/L anatoxin-a, 0.34 ug/L microsystin, and 0.47 ug/L saxitoxin. Cyclindrospermopsin was not detected. The District is ready to post Cuation-level signs for planktonic and benthic mats at the pond.
